  <h2>Why Water Quality Is Critical for Infants</h2>
  <p>Infants are uniquely vulnerable to waterborne contaminants. Their developing organs, smaller body mass, and higher water-to-body-weight ratio mean that contaminants affect them at far lower concentrations than adults. A contaminant level considered safe for an adult can be genuinely harmful to an infant.</p>
  <p>The contaminants of greatest concern for infants include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lead:</strong> No safe level exists for children. Even trace amounts can cause developmental delays, reduced IQ, and behavioral problems. The AAP recommends water contain less than 1 ppb of lead for children — far below the EPA action level of 15 ppb. Homes with plumbing installed before 1986 are at highest risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Nitrates:</strong> Above 10 ppm, nitrates interfere with an infant's ability to carry oxygen in the blood, causing methemoglobinemia (blue baby syndrome). This is primarily a concern for well water users near agricultural areas.</li>
    <li><strong>PFAS:</strong> Forever chemicals accumulate in the body over time and have been linked to immune system effects, developmental delays, and increased cancer risk. They are found in the water supply of an estimated 200 million Americans.</li>
    <li><strong>Bacteria and viruses:</strong> Infants' immune systems are immature. Waterborne pathogens that an adult's body handles without symptoms can cause severe illness in newborns.</li>
    <li><strong>Chlorine byproducts:</strong> While chlorine itself is used for disinfection, the byproducts (trihalomethanes and haloacetic acids) formed when chlorine reacts with organic matter are associated with health risks at chronic exposure levels.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to Look For in a Water Filter for Baby Formula</h2>
  <p>Not all filters provide the level of protection infants need. Here are the specific criteria to prioritize:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>NSF 53 certification for lead:</strong> This is non-negotiable. NSF 53 certifies that a filter reduces lead to below EPA standards. Brita Elite, iSpring RCC7AK, and Waterdrop G3P600 all carry this certification.</li>
    <li><strong>Reverse osmosis for comprehensive protection:</strong> RO systems remove the widest range of contaminants at the highest reduction rates. The iSpring RCC7AK removes 93-98% of TDS, >98.9% of lead, and 96-99% of PFAS. For families with known water quality concerns, RO provides the strongest safety margin.</li>
    <li><strong>Remineralization:</strong> Pure RO water is slightly acidic and stripped of minerals. For infant formula, remineralized RO water (like from the iSpring RCC7AK) restores a healthy mineral balance that supports formula's nutritional profile.</li>
    <li><strong>Consistent filtration quality:</strong> Choose established brands with proven track records and proper NSF certification — not just claims. Over 18,000 verified reviews for the iSpring and 38,000 for the Brita Elite provide real-world confidence.</li>
    <li><strong>Easy maintenance with clear replacement schedules:</strong> When filtering water for an infant, there is no room for guessing about filter condition. Systems with clear replacement indicators or schedules help parents maintain peak performance.</li>
  </ul>

  <ProTip title="The Two-Minute Test for New Parents">
    Buy a TDS meter ($10-15 on Amazon) and test your tap water. If the reading is under 150 ppm and your city's water quality report shows no lead detections, a pitcher with Brita Elite filters provides excellent protection. If TDS is above 300 ppm, or your report shows any lead, nitrates, or PFAS, invest in an RO system. This simple test takes 10 seconds and tells you exactly how much filtration you need for your baby's water.
  </ProTip>

